        {"q": "Under the Microsoft Online Services Data Protection Addendum (DPA), what happens to customer data when a subscription is terminated or expires?", "options": ["Microsoft claims ownership of the data", "Microsoft retains the data indefinitely for marketing", "Microsoft retains the data in a limited-function account for 90 days to allow extraction, after which the data is permanently deleted", "The data is published publicly"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "Microsoft enforces strict data lifecycle policies. Upon termination, administrators have a 90-day grace period to export their data. After 90 days, Microsoft permanently and irreversibly deletes the data from its servers."},
        {"q": "What is the architectural purpose of 'Azure Lighthouse' for Managed Security Service Providers (MSSPs)?", "options": ["To provide a physical firewall", "To allow an MSSP to securely manage Microsoft Sentinel and Defender across hundreds of different customer Azure tenants from a single, centralized portal using delegated access", "To monitor internet outages", "To sync on-premises AD"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Azure Lighthouse provides delegated resource management, enabling MSSPs to perform cross-tenant management (like threat hunting in Sentinel) efficiently without needing to log in and out of individual customer accounts."},
        {"q": "An organization is subject to strict regulatory requirements that mandate all encryption keys used to protect cloud data must be generated and managed entirely by the organization, not Microsoft. Which Purview feature supports this?", "options": ["Customer Lockbox", "Customer Key (Bring Your Own Key - BYOK)", "Microsoft Managed Keys", "BitLocker"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "Customer Key allows organizations to control the root encryption keys used to encrypt data at rest in Exchange, SharePoint, and Teams. If the customer revokes the key, the data instantly becomes unreadable, even to Microsoft."}
